@node story
@title "The Story - How it was born"

    A few years ago I was fooling around in AmigaBASIC =) and
  I thought of a neat idea for a game that would be fun to do.
  The computer thought of a random number, and the person playing
  had to try and figure out what the number was.  At first it was
  pretty simple, with only a text interface, and no computer opponent,
  but it slowly improved until it was almost at its current state.

    I recently discovered a PD Amiga BASIC compiler with some great
  features called ACE.  I immediately downloaded (a download during which I
  was _very_ bored! =) ) it and tried it out.  It had a lot of nice
  features I had always wished for in Amiga BASIC and a more.
  Things like gadgets and bevelboxes and playing IFF samples were finally
  available!  After playing with ACE for the last little while I remebered
  good ol' Guess A Number and realized it would make a good project to
  re-do it.  So I did, and I added some new features like Psychic Ability
  for the computer opponent.  ACE also makes executable files, which is
  a major advantage over the slow interpreted AmigaBASIC.

    If you're into programming with BASIC, then you should download it!



@endnode

@node setup
@title "Setting up Guess A Number - It's almost too easy!"

    Well, I don't really know why I wrote this part, if you have extracted
  all the files from the archive as you did with this file then all you
  need to do is open the drawer that the game's in and copy to where you
  want if it's not already there!  That's all you need to do!
  If you're using a screen or system font besides topaz/8, you might
  experience some problems with the layout of the graphics.
  For now all you can do is set your fonts to topaz/8.

@endnode

@node play
@title "Playing the game - The most important part"

    - The Object -

        In Guess A Number, you try to guess (oh really?) which
      number the computer (but not the computer opponent) is thinking of.
      This number can range from 0 to up to 1008.
      You and the computer opponent take turns trying to get the number,
      until one of you guesses the right number 10 times.

    - Playing The Game -

    When you run Guess A Number, you will see a window asking you
  to choose one of three levels of computer intelligence.

      - Shot In The Dark -

      This one's pretty stupid.  In fact it's about as stupid as it can get.
      It simply guesses random numbers between 0 and the limit (which
      you can set).

      - Educated Guess -

      This is quite intelligent.  It learns as the game progresses, and
      narrows down the possible range as it and you guess too high or
      too low.

      - Psychic Advantage -

      The tough one!  The same as Educated Guess but it has an added
      advantage. If you select this one, you will be asked to select
      the level of its psychic powers after choosing the game limit
      (see below).  The higher the value, the better it is.
      If you move the slider to the far right, it will always guess the
      right number on the first try.

    After you've chosen your opponent, you will then be asked to choose
  the game limit.  This is the highest that the number you're guessing
  can be, ie - if you select 100, the number won't be anything above 100.

    Now the game begins.  The computer will go first.  It will show you
  what number it guesses, and then it will say either # is too high
  or # is too low.  It's important that you pay attention to these numbers
  so that you know where to make your own guess.  Once it has gone, you
  make your guess.  Type in the number and press enter.  You can use ESC
  to clear your guess and backspace to delete the last number from your
  guess.  Again, the game will either say # is too high or # is too low,
  or if you got it right (this happens for the computer too) it will say
  # is RIGHT!!!  Then the winner will get a point and a new round will
  begin with a new number.

    During the game, there are two gadgets at the bottom of the window.
  The first one, 'Give Up', you can click if you want to give up the
  current round.  The game will show you what the number was (doh!) and
  a new round will start.  The second gadget, 'End Game' will end the game
  and take you back to the 'Select Opponent' menu.  If you want to quit
  the game completely at any time, just click the window's close gadget.

@endnode

